{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647142"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18229"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18229"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.11,0.22,0.16,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77476"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10943"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18229"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5113"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25435"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77476"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERickets and osteomalacia are conditions resulting from vitamin D deficiency, affecting bone mineralisation. Rickets occurs in children, while osteomalacia affects adults.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a typical laboratory finding in rickets and osteomalacia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low serum calcium","Low serum phosphate","Elevated alkaline phosphatase","High serum calcium","High serum phosphate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe typical laboratory finding in rickets and osteomalacia is \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated alkaline phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E. This enzyme is increased due to increased osteoblastic activity as the body attempts to mineralise the bone matrix.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow serum calcium\u003C/strong\u003E - While calcium can be low, it is not as consistent a finding as elevated alkaline phosphatase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow serum phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E - Phosphate is often low due to impaired bone mineralisation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh serum calcium\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not typical in rickets or osteomalacia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh serum phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E - Phosphate is usually low, not high, in these conditions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese conditions are characterised by defective bone mineralization due to vitamin D deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rickets and osteomalacia are conditions caused by vitamin D deficiency, leading to impaired bone mineralisation.","Clinical features of rickets in children include bone pain, skeletal deformities, and growth retardation.","Osteomalacia in adults presents with bone pain, muscle weakness, and increased risk of fractures.","Laboratory findings in rickets and osteomalacia include low serum calcium, low phosphate, and elevated alkaline phosphatase."],"references":["Uday S, H\u00f6gler W. Nutritional rickets \u0026 osteomalacia: A practical approach to management. Indian J Med Res. 2020 Oct;152(4):356-367. doi: 10.4103/ijmr.IJMR_1961_19. PMID: 33380700; PMCID: PMC8061584","Uday S, H\u00f6gler W. Nutritional Rickets and Osteomalacia in the Twenty-first Century: Revised Concepts, Public Health, and Prevention Strategies. Curr Osteoporos Rep. 2017 Aug;15(4):293-302. doi: 10.1007/s11914-017-0383-y. Erratum in: Curr Osteoporos Rep. 2017 Oct;15(5):507. doi: 10.1007/s11914-017-0395-7. PMID: 28612338; PMCID: PMC5532418","Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9. doi: 10.2215/CJN.04151206. PMID: 18988698; PMCID: PMC3152283","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18229"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62988"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T08:57:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T08:57:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10943"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77476"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"update